{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583024/1921031001/0177.xml":{"full_text":"PHYSICIAN DUBBED\n8RIGADIERGENERAL\nTrailing Ludicrous Precedent,\nVillage Pus-Paddier Will Be\ncome Pretended Veteran of\nGory Battlefields\nBy HUGH W. ROBERTS\n0 Washington Bureau The Age-Herald\n500 Davidson Building\nWashington, March 8.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Dr. C.\nE. Sawyer of Marion, O., nominated fcy\nPresident Harding today to be a brig\nadier general, will he Confirmed.\nThe democrats will not Interpose ob\njection, and will thus prove themselves\nto be \u201cbigger\u201d than the republicans, who\nwhined \u201cfrom the soul\u201d when President\nWilson sought to elevate Dr. Cary E\nGrayson to the rank of admiral.\nThis does not mean that every demo\ncrat will vote for the confirmation of Hr.\nSawyer. Individuals may vote against\nhis confirmation. But the great bulk or\nthe party will support him, and in so\ndoing will declare the opinion that in\nmaking personal appointments the Presi\ndent should not be handicapped.\nRepublicans are prone to declare to\nday that the Grayson confirmation was\nthe precedent on which President Hard\ning based the nomination of Dr. Saw\nyer. But as Senator Harris of Georgia\npointed out this afternoon, the cases are\nnot analagoos. Dr. Grayson has served\ntwo Presidents prior to his \u201cadoption\u201d by\nPresident Wilson, and his elevation was\nin the nature of a promotion. Dr. Saw\nyer ha a private citizen, and his elevation\nis the result simply of an arbitrary de\nsire upon the chief executive.\nUNDERWOOD SILENT\nSenator Underwood, democratic leader,\ndid not discuss the Sawyer nomination\ntoday from a party standpoint. It is\nknown, however, that it is his idea that\nthe President in making personal ap\npointments should not subject him to the\nnagging of Congress. It is sare to predict,\nthat he himself will vote for continua\ntion. Senator Harris, while stressing the\nI difference In the Grayson and the Saw\nI yer cases, declared that he would vote\nfor confirmation.\n\u201cThe President,\" said he, \u201cis of such im\nI portance to the country that his health\nmost me safeguarded. It is proper that\nsuch guardianship be intrusted to the\nI man the President selects.\n\"During tne administration or ^resident\nWilson th\u00a9 republicans continually inter\nposed objections to his nomination or\nmen to purely personal positions. They\n1 fretted at great length regarding the ap\nIpointment of Dr. Grayson. They repeat\nledlr attempted to eheckmate the Press\nI dent In his effort to fill positions In th#\nI cabinet, th\u00a9 fight against Attorney Gen\n|eral Palmer being a case in point,\n\u201cI think th\u00a9 democrats should and will\n[prove themselves of bigger spirit than\nthe republicans. For one, I will support\n[Dr. Sawyer, and I feel confident that th\u00a9\n[democrats who formally oppose him will\nI be few Indeed/'\nI# There is another reason why th\u00a9 dem\nlocrats will stand by Sawyer. Sometime\n[ago, as is recalled, President Wilson pro*\nlmoted Col. Robert E. Noble, an Ala\nIbamian in the department of the surgeon\n[general, to the rank of brigadier gen\nleral. The republicans strenuously op\n1 posed his confirmation. But three repub\nlliean senators voted for his confirmation\nland as result he was confirmed. One\nof the three was President Harding,\nthen Senator Harding.\nThe vote of Harding was cast as result\nlof persuasion by Dr. Sawyer, who came\n\u25a0from Marion to Washington for the spe\n|e;fic purpose of \u201cpulling him over.\u201d As\n\u25a0all democrats supported Noble, they were\nnaturally grateful to Harding and to Dr.\nSawyer.\nBut while this incfdent may be influ\nlential, it is not controlling. Democratic\n[support of Sawyer results from desire of\n[democratic senators to prove themselves\n[other than politicians of the \u201csmall cai\nlibre.\u2019* variety.\nMonesjiE\nWhen the Children Cough,\nRub Musterole on Throats\nand Chests\nNo telling h